Greek Stock Preview: Coca-Cola HBC, OTE, NBG, Piraeus Bank

-- B y   T o m   S t o u k a s
-- 
2011-02-11T07:35:38Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-11/greek-stock-preview-coca-cola-hbc-ote-nbg-piraeus-bank.html
The following stocks may be active
in the Greek market. Symbols are in parentheses after company
names and prices are from the previous close.  The benchmark ASE Index fell 58.52, or 3.5 percent, to
1,632.06. The FTSE/ASE 20 Index of the country’s biggest
companies dropped 3.9 percent to 762.89 and the Cypriot General
Index declined 5 percent to 1,201.40.  Bank of Cyprus Pcl (BOC GA): Andreas Eliades, the chief
executive officer of Cyprus’s biggest bank, said more market
turbulence is expected, after the first “shock” as countries
steer through the financial crisis.  “As a result of the big imbalances we have already lived
through the first big shock for markets and we expect
uncertainty and turbulence to continue until we are led to a
point of a new global balance,” Eliades said during a speech in
Cyprus last night. The stock dropped 5 percent to 3.25 euros.  EFG Eurobank Ergasias SA  (EUROB GA) fell 9 percent to 4.33.  Alpha Bank AE  (ALPHA GA) declined 6.5 percent to 4.49 euros.       Coca-Cola Hellenic Bottling Co. SA (EEEK GA): The world’s
second-biggest bottler of Coke soft drinks had its rating cut to
“neutral” from “buy” at Goldman Sachs Group Inc. The stock
fell 0.5 percent to 21.29 euros.    Hellenic Telecommunications Organization SA  (HTO GA):  Greece ’s largest telephone services provider signed a 900
million-euro ($1.22 billion) revolving credit facility with
eight Greek and eight international banks. Hellenic Telecom
plans to draw down 600 million euros of the loan to repay a 1.5
billion-euro bond maturing on Feb. 14, according to an e-mailed
 statement  from the Athens-based company. The stock declined 3.2
percent to 7.84 euros.    National Bank of Greece SA  (ETE GA): Finansbank AS (FINBN
TI), the Turkish unit of Greece’s largest bank, said profit
increased 41 percent to 914.7 million liras ($575 million) last
year. Net income at Finansbank rose from 650.1 million liras in
2009, according to a statement to the  Istanbul Stock Exchange .
National Bank shares dropped 4.51 percent to 7.41 euros.    Piraeus Bank SA  (TPEIR GA): Greece’s fourth-largest lender
separated the position of chief executive officer and chairman
naming Stavros Lekkakos, a managing director, as new chief
executive officer. Michalis Sallas remains chairman of the bank,
according to an Athens bourse  filing . The stock dropped 4.9
percent to 1.56 euros.    Proton Bank SA  (PRO GA): The Greek lender said it issued 60
million euros in 10-year subordinated notes through a private
placement, according to an e-mailed statement from the bank. The
stock dropped 11.5 percent to 85 euro cents.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Tom Stoukas in Athens at 
 astoukas@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:  David Merritt  at 
 dmerritt1@bloomberg.net . 